PART 5: MULTIPLES OF 7 IN H SPECTRUM
======================================================================

Multiples of 7 that are odd (potential H values):
  7 × 1 = 7: MISSING
  7 × 3 = 21: MISSING
  7 × 5 = 35: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 7 = 49: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 9 = 63: MISSING
  7 × 11 = 77: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 13 = 91: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 15 = 105: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 17 = 119: MISSING
  7 × 19 = 133: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 21 = 147: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 23 = 161: MISSING
  7 × 25 = 175: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 27 = 189: ACHIEVABLE
  7 × 29 = 203: MISSING

--- 189 = max H(7) ---
189 = 3³ × 7 = 27 × 7
Since 7 is forbidden as a component factor,
189 must come from a SINGLE connected component with I(Ω,2)=189
OR from a different factorization not involving 7.
Check: 189 = 3 × 63, 9 × 21, 27 × 7
All factorizations involve 7 or 21 (=3×7) or 63 (=9×7)
So 189 MUST come from a single connected Ω with I(Ω,2)=189
This means Ω has a single large connected component!

